article.description:
Katie Douglas scored 13 points and
matched her career high with five steals to lead the Connecticut Sun to a 61-43 win over the New York Liberty on Friday night.
article.headline: Douglas matches career high with five steals
article.linkText: Douglas helps Sun shine again against Liberty
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Katie Douglas made sure Becky Hammon
never got comfortable.

Douglas led the Connecticut Sun with 13 points while shutting
down the New York Liberty's leading scorer in the 61-43 win Friday
night. Six inches taller than Hammon, Douglas gave the 5-foot-6
guard few looks.

"She never found her comfort zone," Douglas said. "Just my
length and being able to bother her at the point guard position may
have played a part of that."

Hammon finished with just two points, 11 below her average.
Douglas also matched her career high with five steals.

"I just wanted to come out and concentrate on defense first and
disrupt a little of their timing," Douglas said.

The win snapped the Sun's three-game losing streak and
brightened their playoff hopes with just five games left in the
season. It was Connecticut's first game back in the Mohegan Sun
arena since the monthlong Olympic break, and it didn't take the Sun
long to settle in.

New York was unable to sustain any runs in the first half and
never found its rhythm against the Connecticut pressure defense.
Elena Baranova led New York with nine points and nine boards.

"We just harassed them," Sun coach Mike Thibault. "It was
playoff kind of basketball. I can't remember a team I ever coached
when not a single opposing player scored in double figures."

The Liberty had been the hottest team in the Eastern Conference
at the August break, winning six of their last nine. That run
included a 14-point blowout over Connecticut at Radio City Music
Hall on July 31.

There wasn't a Rockette in sight this time.

"It goes back to winning on your home court," New York coach
Pat Coyle said. "You play with a lot more energy. We did a better
job of executing at home and they did the same thing here."

Taj McWilliams-Franklin added 11 points for the Sun and rookie
Lindsay Whalen finished with six assists in guiding the Sun's
uptempo attack.

The Sun built a 15-point lead late in the first half with
transition baskets off Liberty turnovers. McWilliams-Franklin's
driving layup with 2:03 capped a 15-4 run and gave the Sun its
largest lead at 32-17.

New York made the most of the final minutes, however, closing
out the period on a 7-0 run and trailed 32-24 at the break. The
Liberty's 19 second-half points were an all-time low for a Sun
opponent.

Douglas converted a three-point play to open the second half,
kicking off a 7-2 run and the Liberty would get no closer than 10
the rest of the way.

New York remains just one game ahead of Connecticut in the
conference. They'll meet twice more in a home-and-home before the
season ends.
